### PRA*S*NA I, PA*T*ALA 2, KHA*ND*A 7.

1\. Or he may rise silently.

2\. Nor shall he (in going away) move around his teacher with his left
hand turned towards him; he shall go away after having walked around him
with his right side turned towards him.

3\. He shall not look at a naked woman. <span
id="fr_216"></span>[3](#fn_215.md)

4\. He shall not cut the (leaves or flowers) of herbs or trees, in order
to smell at them. <span id="fr_217"></span>[4](#fn_216.md)

<span id="page_26">p. 26</span>

5\. He shall avoid (the use of) shoes, of an umbrella a chariot, and the
like (luxuries). <span id="fr_218"></span>[5](#fn_217.md)

6\. He shall not smile.

7\. If he smiles, he shall smile covering (the mouth with his hand);
thus says a Brâhma*n*a.

8\. He shall not touch a woman with his face, in order to inhale the
fragrance of her body.

9\. Nor shall he desire her in his heart.

10\. Nor shall he touch (a woman at all) without a particular
reason. <span id="fr_219"></span>[10](#fn_218.md)

11\. A Brâhma*n*a declares, 'He shall be dusty, be shall have dirty
teeth, and speak the truth.' <span id="fr_220"></span>[11](#fn_219.md)

12\. Those teachers, who instructed his teacher in that science which he
(the pupil) studies with him, (are to be considered as) spiritual
teachers (by the pupil). <span id="fr_221"></span>[12](#fn_220.md)

13\. But if (a teacher), before the eyes of his (pupil), embraces the
feet of any other persons, then he (the pupil also) must embrace their
feet, (as long as he remains) in that (state of studentship). <span
id="fr_222"></span>[13](#fn_221.md)

<span id="page_27">p. 27</span>

14\. If (a pupil) has more than one teacher, the alms (collected by him)
are at the disposal of him to whom he is (just then) bound. <span
id="fr_223"></span>[14](#fn_222.md)

15\. When (a student) has returned home (from his teacher), he shall
give (whatever he may obtain by begging or otherwise) to his mother.

16\. The mother shall give it to her husband;

17\. (And) the husband to the (student's) teacher.

18\. Or he may use it for religious ceremonies. <span
id="fr_224"></span>[18](#fn_223.md)

19\. After having studied as many (branches of) sacred learning as he
can, he shall procure in a righteous manner the fee for (the teaching
of) the Veda (to be given to his teacher), according to his power. <span
id="fr_225"></span>[19](#fn_224.md)

20\. But, if the teacher has fallen into distress, he may take (the fee)
from an Ugra or from a *S*ûdra. <span id="fr_226"></span>[20](#fn_225.md)

21\. But some declare, that it is lawful at any time to take the money
for the teacher from an Ugra or from a *S*ûdra.

<span id="page_28">p. 28</span>

22\. And having paid (the fee), he shall not boast of having done so.

23\. And he shall not remember what he may have done (for his teacher).

24\. He shall avoid self-praise, blaming others, and the like. <span
id="fr_227"></span>[24](#fn_226.md)

25\. If he is ordered (by his teacher to do something), he shall do just
that.

26\. On account of the incompetence of his teacher, (he may go) to
another (and) study (there). <span id="fr_228"></span>[26](#fn_227.md)

27\. He shall behave towards his teacher's wife as towards the teacher
himself, but he shall not embrace her feet, nor eat the residue of her
food. <span id="fr_229"></span>[27](#fn_228.md)

28\. So also (shall he behave) towards him who teaches him at (the
teacher's) command, <span id="fr_230"></span>[28](#fn_229.md)

29\. And also to a fellow-student who is superior (in learning and
years). <span id="fr_231"></span>[29](#fn_230.md)

30\. He shall behave to his teacher's son (who is superior to himself in
learning or years) as to his teacher, but not eat the residue of his
food. <span id="fr_232"></span>[30](#fn_231.md)

31\. Though he may have returned home, the

<span id="page_29">p. 29</span>

behaviour towards his (teacher and the rest) which is prescribed by the
rule of conduct settled by the agreement (of those who know the law,
must be observed by him to the end),

