ceremonies, i.e. the wedding and the like. For them he may use it
optionally. He, i.e. on failure of the teacher; the father, on failure
of the father; the mother, on failure of all (the pupil)
himself.'--Haradatta.

<span id="fn_224"></span>[27:19](sbe0210.htm#fr_225.md) Manu II, 245 and
